      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented SQA plan, version control, and regression test suite for the FEA solver (Ansys Mechanical 2023 R2).",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2023 R2 is a commercially validated solver with documented SQA procedures. Internal regression test suite covers linear-elastic and contact-nonlinear benchmarks relevant to the pedicle screw model. Version control records confirm the model files used for submission are traceable to a tagged repository release."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification against analytical solutions or Method of Manufactured Solutions for beam bending and contact problems.",
      "rationale": "Cantilever beam bending and Hertzian contact benchmarks were reproduced within 0.5% of analytical solutions using the same element types (SOLID186, CONTA174) employed in the pedicle screw model. Results are documented in the solver verification report SVR-2023-07."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating QoI change <2% between successive refinements; GCI reported.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study (coarse 1.2 mm, medium 0.8 mm, fine 0.5 mm global seed) yielded GCI of 1.4% for stiffness and 1.8% for yield force. Medium mesh selected for production runs as the converged solution. Discretization error contribution to total uncertainty budget is documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual convergence criteria documented and Newton-Raphson iteration force residuals below 0.1% of reaction force.",
      "rationale": "All nonlinear load steps converged to force residuals below 0.05% of the peak reaction force. No diverged increments were observed across the 11-construct ensemble. Solver log files are archived alongside the model package."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of boundary condition application, load magnitudes, and contact definitions by a second analyst.",
      "rationale": "A second FEA analyst independently reviewed the model setup, confirmed correct application of ASTM F1717 boundary conditions (fixed inferior block, displacement-controlled superior block at 1 mm/min equivalent), and verified contact pairs at screw-rod and screw-block interfaces. No discrepancies were identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification that linear-elastic with plasticity model form is appropriate for titanium alloy pedicle screw under quasi-static bending; sensitivity analysis on constitutive model parameters.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity (BISO) was selected for Ti-6Al-4V ELI rod and screw bodies based on published stress-strain data. Elastic-only and Ramberg-Osgood alternatives were evaluated; BISO produced the best agreement with experimental load-displacement curves in the post-yield regime. Sensitivity of yield force to tangent modulus (±20%) was within ±3% of QoI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from lot-specific testing; geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of test articles; uncertainty quantification on all primary inputs.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (E, sigma_y, E_t) were taken from lot-specific certificate-of-conformance testing of the Ti-6Al-4V ELI rod and screw stock. Geometric dimensions were obtained from CMM measurements of the actual test constructs. Uncertainty propagation via Monte Carlo (N=1000) quantified combined input uncertainty at ±4.1% on stiffness and ±5.3% on yield force."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test constructs from production-representative hardware; traceability of test articles to manufacturing lot documented.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from production-representative hardware. Manufacturing lot traceability is documented in the test report. Constructs span two independent test laboratories, providing cross-laboratory reproducibility data."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Testing performed at multiple clinically relevant loading rates or displacement levels to characterize rate sensitivity.",
      "rationale": "All bench testing was conducted at a single displacement rate (1 mm/min) per ASTM F1717. No multi-rate or multi-displacement-level testing was performed. This factor is below the required level; the gap is acknowledged as a limitation of the standardized test method. Clinical loading rates span a broader range, but the quasi-static protocol is accepted by FDA precedent for this device class."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented mapping between FEA input parameters and experimentally measured quantities; discrepancies quantified and incorporated into validation uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Each FEA model instance was parameterized using CMM-measured geometry and lot-specific material data from the corresponding physical construct. Mapping between experimental measurements and model inputs is documented in the input equivalency matrix (IEM-COU1-v2). Residual discrepancies in rod diameter (±0.02 mm) and screw thread form were quantified and their effect on QoI bounded via sensitivity analysis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all QoIs; pre-specified acceptance bounds documented prior to simulation.",
      "rationale": "Pre-specified acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96) were documented in the validation plan VP-COU1-2025 prior to running production simulations. All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) met both criteria. E/uval values of 0.87, 1.42, and 1.61 confirm that model-experiment agreement is within combined experimental and simulation uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification that stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are clinically and regulatorily relevant QoIs for pedicle screw construct performance.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness characterizes the construct's resistance to deformation under physiological loading. Yield force indicates the onset of permanent deformation. Force at 40 mm displacement is the FDA-accepted surrogate for construct fatigue and ultimate failure potential under ASTM F1717. All three QoIs are directly cited in FDA guidance for spinal implant 510(k) submissions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities use the same device geometry, material, and loading protocol as the COU; any differences between validation and COU contexts are documented and bounded.",
      "rationale": "The validation constructs are geometrically and materially identical to the COU device. The ASTM F1717 test protocol is the same standardized method used for regulatory submission. The FEA model assessed here is the same model ensemble (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) used in the COU prediction. No extrapolation beyond the validated geometry or loading regime is required for the COU."
    }
  ],
